{"/service/ndnp/ohi/batch_ohi_alastor_ver02/data/sn78003992/0034058093A/1958032801/0271.xml":{"full_text":"So Labor\nMay Know\nDow this country Jiave to have a\n.major depression before Congress sad\nthe Admtaisbatian oea he persuaded\nto adopt serious reforms designed to\ntoake future depressions less severe T\nThe question has some pertinence in\nthe light of the record.\nIn to* first five years of too New\nDeed a great outpouring of legislation\nestablished systems that ere now\nrecognised ae built-in stabilizers of\nour economy. They Include unemploy\ni ment compensation, social security,\nthe Fair labor Standards Ant, the\nWalab-Haaley Ant requiring the pre\nvailing wage on government contracts,\nplus the Wagner'Act, even though\nthat has been modified by Taft-Hart\nley.\nBut tide burst of creative energy\nfollowed three years at intense na\ntional suffering ending with between\none-fourth and one-third of the work\nere left jobless. It was encouraged by\nRoosevelt\u2019s energy and boldness. Even\nso, the steam had run out by mld-1938.\nNow we aw in the third postwar\nand It looks like the moat\nBut leaders in Congress,\nas well as Republican,\nter declined to -make a\nparty Issue of the two substantial pro\nposed reforms that would make a per\neoatrlbutlon to checking re\nhem before they\nNo action has been slated on fed\neral minimum standards for unem\nployment compensation and on a ma\njor step to broaden coverage under\nthe Fair labor Standards Act\nExpansion of\u2018minimum wages to\nmillions of white-collar workers, in\ncluding overtime pay after 40 hours,\nwould give the same social protection\nto these groups that 24 million already\nhave. Moreover, it would substantially\nincrease purchasing power, an in\ncreasingly important factor in eco\nnomic health.\nowl standards in state unemploy\nment systems would restore the pro\ngram to whet R was eppoMd to be\u2014\naa assure ace of approximate half-pay\nto the worker thrown out of a Job. It\nweald tenreaee the counteraction sup\nposed to eome into play to prevent\na renewloa from spree fling by feeding\nan Itself.\n.-These refornw are not innovations\nfrom which the Administration and\nthe Democratic congressional leaders\n-might reasonably shrink. They pro\npose simply to build on already-estab\nlished principles. Bills are ready, in\nterminable hearings have been held,\nthe testimony of conflicting groups is\nBut nothing happens, and there is\nno assurance that anything will hap\npen. Apparently the oouatry has to be\nworse off.\n__.\nHep, Winfield K. Denton, an Indi\nana Democrat, tells in a news letter\nto constituents how he accompanied\nhis state\u2019s Gov. Harold Handley (R)\nIn a pentagon visit seeking defense\ncontracts for Indiana industry.\nA worthy recognition of Indiana\u2019s\n\"sorry unemployment situation,\u201d Den\nton remarks, but he can\u2019t understand\nwhy Handley doesn\u2019t use \"other re\nsources right under his nose which\nalso could help relieve toe state\u2019s\nlack of jobs.\u201d\nItem: By putting up $48 million,\nTmti.rt could obtain $134 million in\nfederal highway funds now \u2019Tying\nIdle\u201d the state won\u2019t furnish the re\nquired \"matching\" money.\nOther items; Indiana has \u201cone of\ni toe poorest reoorda for accepting what\nto offered,\u201d either waking low or\nnet participating at aB to tederal\natatec programs far welfare, vocation\nal mhe Wlltatlon and rural Ubrariee.\nDenton says tost Hondley and pre\nvious Republic administrations have\ntaken toe viewpoint that as \u201ca mat\nter of principle\u201d they taoulda\u2019t take\ntoo much federal money. He thinks\n'it to ahemd.\nsreany (Mr\nto the ffand\ni take the\ngoveraors,\nVenezuela Again\nILO Member\nTmmk hM rejoined the Inti\n^'tAbor OgnnisaUon to make every\noounixycf the Americas a memtwr for\nS| the tint time, Dir.-Gen. David A\n?:Mamwomwt.\nthe HO (ma the time tt wae founded\nhuuauiun.\nIt withdrew in 1806. effective two\njure leter, under HO rulea, In a\n3?; ttepote over the expulsion of a Dutch\nworker delegate. A. Vermeuleu, to a\niinotlnt nf the HO Petmtaun Indue*\ntxyCbmmlttee In Cancan.\nt\n'Jv* i> ^s \u2018*r\n'v s O -i.;' \u2022_ t,\nONE\nFOR ALL\nALL FOR\nONE\nsVy.\np:\nVoL 36 \u2014No. 13\nAKRON,, OHIO, FRIDAY, MARCH 28, 1868\n$S.M PEE YEA*\nOhio Catholic Bishops\nOnce Again Protest\n*Right-to-Work\u2019 ,.-v\nThe six Catholic Bishops of Ohio reaffirmed their stand\nagainst so-called \u201cright-to-work\u201d laws in a public statement issued\nlast Friday through the Ohio Catholic Welfare Conference.\nThe Bishops of the six Ohio dioceses said that the proposed\nanti-union shop amendment to the Ohio Constitution \u201cwould not\nsolve our problems, but might lead to more intensified struggle.\u201d\nThe Bishops issued a similar statement in 1955 against enact\nment of so-called \u201cright-to-work\u201d laws. V\nn\u00bb latest statement against MCbf\nlam was signed by Archbishop Karl\nJ. Alter of Cincinnati, Archbishop Ed\nward F. Hoban of Cleveland, Bishop\nBhnmet M. Walsh of Youngstown,\nBishop George I. Behring of Toledo,\nBishop John K, Musslo of Steuben\nville, and Bishop Clarence G. Isscn\nmann of Oatambtu.\n\"Theje are certain abuses which\nsometimes creep into the labor move\nment,\u201d the Bishops declared, \"but\nwe are convinced that \u2018Right To\nWork\u2019 lawn are not the proper means\nto correct them.\u201d\nHie statement said that a man does\nnot have the unconditional right to\nwork in any and every industry or\nbusiness at wilL\u201d The Bishops ''as\nserted: v, \u2022'_*\n\"For reasons of social Justice, It\nmay be desirable and often advan\ntageous to the common good that a\nman\u2019s right be restricted by certain\nspecified conditions. One of these im\nposed conditions may require that he\nbelong to a labor union or at least\nbe obliged to Join the union subse\nquently, so as to share responsibility\nwith Us fellow workmen in support\nof the onion.\u201d\nThe Bishops Said they did not be\nlieve the state government should in\ntervene in the union shop issue. They\nsaid they would oppose a state law re\nquiring union membership just as\nI AM Defense\nFund Voted\nA special defense fund from which\nstrikers will be paid benefits of $35\nweekly has been approved in a refer\nendum vote by members of the Ma\nchinists, Secretary-Treasurer Eric\nPeterson announced.\nHie vote, conducted in local lodges\nduring February, was 110487 in favor\nof the proposal, 65,891 against. A rec\nord-breaking 759 lodges participated\nin the balloting.\nThe membership action amended\nthe IAM constitution so as to In\ncrease from $1.80 to $2 a month tire\nportion of each member's dues which\ngoes to the grand lodge. Of this, 50\ncents Is to be set aside in the special\nstrike fond, which may be used for\nno other purpose. Benefits will be paid\nwhen $8 raHUnn has been accumu\nlated.\nHie increased per capita- aim\nwill give each IAM member a sub\nscription to tiie Machinist, the union\u2019s\nweekly newspaper, and pay for bend\ning up to $2,500 local and district\nlodge financial officers.\nCONFAB ON WORKMEN\u2019S\nCOMPENSATION SET 1\nA half-century of effort to provide\nmedical care, income and rehabilita\ntion for the worker Injured on the job\nwill be reviewed at the AFL-CHO\nNational Conference on Workmen\u2019s\nCompensation to be held April 16 to\n17 in toe Sheraton-Patrk Hotel in\nWashington,\nDelegations are expected from na\ntional and international. unions, de\npartments and state central bodies.\na re\n\n\n\u25a0in\nQuestion Tax\nDeduction by\nOhio C of C\nThe tax deductibility status of dues\npayments to the Ohio Chamber at\nCommerce are being jeopardized by\nthe officers of that group.\nThat was the charge made last\nweek by Howard Metzenbaum, gen\neral counsel of the Ohio State Federa\ntion of tabor, in an address to the\nHarvard Business School Club in\nCleveland.\n\u201cUnder the law,\u201d Metzenbaum\nsaid, \u201cyou can\u2019t do indirectly that\nwhich it la illegal to do directly. Busi\nness organizations may not deduct\npolitical contributions under the In\nternal Revenue Code, this includes\ncontributions to support the proposed\nconstitutional amendment outlawing\nthe union shop in Ohio.\u201d\nThe labor lawyer pointed out that\ndue* to the Ohio Chamber of Com\nmerce are now deductible but \u201cthe\nChamber\u2019s expenditure of Its funds\nIn support of the compulsory open\nshop amendment makes It a political\norganization.\u201d\nMetzenbaum quoted from a bulle\ntin put out by supporters of the com\npulsory open shop proposal which\ncautions that \u201cthe Internal Revenue\nDepartment states that contributions\nto TOight to Work\u2019 by individuals,\ncompanies and corporations are legal\nbut are not tax deductible contribu\ntions.\u2019\u2019\nHe also referred to numerous Ohio\nChamber of Commerce Bulletins, in\ncluding a recent \u201cpersonal appeal\u201d\nfrom President Harry W. Arnold for\nassistance in obtaining petition circu\nlators and workers to assist in the\ndrive for toe compulsory open shop\namendment.\nlag of Akron Labor Connell, i|L\nCIO, is aehedaied to be held to toe\nsailtorii of Oiihto Local No.\n5 at 701 South Mato Street ea\nMonday night, April 28th. The\nmuttnt win be called to order at\n8:00 o\u2019clock bjLff. --f\nTOo ananas manat eoaotMatoa the\nofHetol aettfteatlsn of the msstlaf\nwik hold lto\nday evening, April 24th.\n\u2022tooted number of federal employee\nby Congteoe and at tbe request of\nPres. Theodore Booeevelt finds state\nlaws not only behind the times, bat\nstill felling\u2019 to meet even \u2018The limited\nobjectives which its early advocates\nhad set for It,\u201d according to AIL\nCIO President George Meany.\n'It is my wish,\u201d Mid Meany in his\ncall to the-conference, \u201cthat the con\nference review the experience of SO\nRUBBER workers see\nCONGRESS IN ACTION S\nxnejr came, u*y saw and they\nlearned.\nAnd, today, M United Rubber\nWorkers (URW) anion members are\nback in their home towns across the\ncountry, telling fellow unionists, their\nfamilies and friends what they learned\nafter a five-day inside view of the\nFederal government in action.\nThe 29 staled the government\nfirst-hand at the first in a series of\nthree 1958 URW-eponsored f oglele\nfive Institutes ia Washington.\nSimilar Institutes, under the direc\ntion of URW General fiecretary\nTreas. Desmond Walker are ecfaed\nuled there March 30- April 3 and\nApril 27-May 1.\n\u201cBefore, I had to just listen to\nsomeone explain something that was\nup in Congress,,but I didn\u2019t really\nknow shout it myself so that I knew\nthe why of it,\u201d Evelyn Richard, mem\nber; of local 511 In Winchester, Va.,\nsaid.\n\u201cFor instance, when someone men\ntioned the Kennedy-McCarthy BUI\nthat was in Congress, I really didn\u2019t\nknow what it. was ail shout,\u2019\u2019 she ex\nplained. \u201cNow I know exactly haw\nit would set up new minimum unem\npioyment compensation benefits and I\nreally know why I\u2019m for It in my own\nmind.\u201d\nHe comment is typical of that of\nthe other students, many who were in\nWashington for the first time.\nA Jam-packed program as varied\nas the Washington weather kept the\nstudents on the go from 8 A. M. to 10\nP. M. every day. They had peBtieal\nscience for breakfast, lunch and din\nner, with in-between eaaehs of visits\nto the Senate, House of Beproaenta\ntiven, a Senate hearing, the Capitol,\nWhite House, AFL-OIO flee dquarturn\nand the Moroeeaa Tmhasey.\nThe pace was fast from the opening\nsession at 4 P. M. Sunday until the\nfinal putting-into-aotton-what-you\nhave-leamed session Thursday after\nnoon.\nA briefing on the institute by Walk\ner, William Allen, URW Washington\nrepresentative, and Joe Glaser, URW\neducation director, opened the insti\ntute. Then tiie students took an oral\nquiz. It was to self-test what they did\nor didn\u2019t know about government\n\"The primary duty of Congress is\n\nA Cross, or A Torch, or A Living Tree?\nBr BUTN TAYLOB\nEach of as has a burden to carry. Each of us has a load that\nseems too great for our strength. With one it may be a burden of\ngrief, with another poverty, with another ill-health\u2014or heavy re\nsponsibilities, heartaches, misunderstanding, stifled talents, ex\npected opportunities that never materialize.\nWhat we make of these burdens, depends upon ourselves\nalone. They are our load of wood, which we alone can carry.\nTo some their burdens -are a cross under which the body is\nbowed. The valiant may strive to carry the cross but each step be\ncomes more difficult as the load weighs down the spirit and tires\nthe heart. A few glory in martyrdom\u2014-but being a martyr is a\nlonely life.\nTo others their burdens are a torch. Out of the dead wood of\ntheir lives they make a flaming beacon to light the way ahead for\nthose who follow. They use their sorrows bravely as they face\nthem boldly. The light they give forth is the high flame of cour\nage, brightening the paths of those around them.\nStill others make of their burdens a living tree. They assume\nthe thankless task of planting their griefs that out of them may\ngrow a living thing\u2014a tree which will give shade and comfort to\nthe weary traveler? a place of beauty in the world, where the\nsong of nesting birds may bring solace to the ear as the leafy\nbranches give rest to the heart. They tend their Borrows, not to\nremember them\u2014but because their griefs have made them warm\nhearted, ready to give to others even that which they may never\npossess for themselves.\nTo bear a sorrow bravely is a noble thing. But, I think, to bear\na burden graciously is the better' part. Once I know a woman\nwho was living a life of what seemed utter drudgery, added to by\nthe ingratitude and querulousness of the one whose burden she\nwas trying to lift. When someone commiserated with her on her\nlot and commented on her cheerful, considerate attitude in face of\nprovocation, she said: \u201cWell, if I am going to be a martyr, the least\nI can do is to be a gTacious one. There is no sense in both of us\nbeing uncomfortable.\"\nI\u2019ve remembered that, and in my own dark hours have tried\nto follow her teachings. She planted a living tree whose seed has\nbeen sown far and wide.\nWe can make of our burdens a cross, or a torch, or a Uving\ntree.\nWhich do you do?\nCandidates,,.*.\nHie Summit County Labor Noaw ia the odj\nLabor Paper published in Summit County, ft\ncovers a field diet you cun reach in no other way.\nTake advantage of its Paid Circulation tor your\nPolitical Advertising;\nCards Folds rt Ballots\nI CAMPAIGN LITERATURE\nThe Exchange Printing Co.\n920 SOUTH HIGH SHOOT FO 2-1110\n\u201cAction Now,\u201d\nIs Requested\nBy Labor\nThis went recession since the end of\nWorld War H gripped the country\nthis week as signs multiplied that the\neconomic outlook would get worse be\nfore any real recovery sets in.\nAll the major yardsticks of eco\nnomic activity pointed downward\nfirmly established the 1957-58 reces\nsion as exceeding in intensity and\ndamage the setbacks suffered in 1948\n49 sad 1953-54, and Labor urged Con\ngress and the administration to act\nat once.\nThis was the situation as Congress\nand the Administration scurried for\nsolutions:\n1\u2014The Federal Reserve Board re\nported a 3 point drop in industrial\nproduction in February bringing ttiA\ndecline in the current recession to 15\npoints or 10.3 per cent\u2014more than the\ndrop in either of the previous postwar\nslumps.\nThe Board summarized the eco\nnomic situation:\n\"Recession in economic activity\n(Ooattoned on Page Few)\nOrders Study of\nBlue Cross in\nNew York\nGovernor Averell Harriman of New\nYork has asked the legislature to ap\npropriate $100,000 for a study of the\nBlue Ooss and Blue Shield programs.\nIts aims, he said in a message, is\nto enable the State Insurance Dept\nmore intelligently to act on applica\ntions for rate changes, and secondarily\nto determine if cost can be cut so as to\nlessen the need for rate increases.\nHarriman\u2019s request is substantially\nthe proposal Assistant Director Dane\nKirkland, of the AFL-CIO Dept of\nSocial Security, made at hearings\non the New York City Bine Cross\u2019 ap\nplication for a 40 per cent rate boost.\nThis would have amounted to $18 mil\nlion a year, and was rejected with ia\nstraetkms to the Blue Cross to operate\non its excess reserves tor a while.\nThe governor also asked the legis\nlature to out the reserve requirements\nof non-profit hospital inumnc* com\npanies from the present 25 per cent\nof the previous year\u2019s premiums to 15\nper cent. This would release |1L8 mil\nlion to meet current Blue Cross ope\nrating costs.\nIMPROVED JOBLESS PAY\nURGED BY MITCHELL\nHie Elsenhower Administration,\nwhich has been appealing without too\nmuch success to the states to streng\nthen their unemployment compensa\ntion systems, has launched a new\nappeal for improvement*.\nLabor Secretary James P. Mitchell\nhas sent a letter to the governors of\nthe tt states, Hawaii and dlsslrs, sug\ngesting that \u201cIn this period of eco\nnomic readjustment and Its sttrailsnl\nunemployment,\" they take a warn look\n1 The pace In Congress seemed un\nusually active as the party leaden\nencouraged rapid committe votes on\na broad range of measures to cre\nate Jobs directly or stimulate the\neconomy and as the House joined the\nSenate in passing two resolutions ex\npressing the \u201csense of Congress\u201d\nmilitary and civilian spending should\nbe hastened as tnuch as \u201cpractical.\u201d\nBut action was postponed at least\nuntil mid-April on major measures\nsuch as tax relief, federal funds to\nsupplement unemployment compen\nsation and prompt increases in social\nsecurity benefits.\nHearings were scheduled but no ac\ntion was dose on another major anti\nrecession measure urged by the AFT\u00bb\n<30\u2014the Kennedy-McCarthy bill to\nestablish permanent federal minimum\nstandards to require state Jobless\ncompensation systems to function as\nthey were originally designed to func\ntion.\nThe Administration, which early in\nMarch refused to moke up its mind on\ntax reduction until April 10, when\nthe March unemployment figures be\ncome officially \u201cavailable,\" suddenly\nshowed a desire for still, another\nmonth of fence-sitting.\nPresident George Meany and other\nAFL-CIO Executive Committee mem\nbers had urged President Eisenhower\nto move for an \u201cImmediate\u201d tax cut,\nwarning things were getting \u201cworse\nrather than better.\u201d Bat on March 18\nSenator William F. Knowland (R\nCalif.) said after a long White House\nvisit by GOP congressional leaders\nthat a decision could not be reached\nfor \u201cat least\u201d two months.\n(Continued oa Pago Hour)\nRed Brutality\nA month-long exhibit of dramatic\npictures, demonstrating Communist 5\nbrutality and Soviet aggression is be\ning placed on display at Union Station\nin Washington.\nThe pictorial exhibit, entitled \u201cThe\nSoviet Empire: 1917-1958\u201d, is pre\nsented by the AFL-dO and the As-\nsembly of Captive European Nations.\nA formal program, Including repre\nsentatives of labor, the national gov\nernment and refugees from behind\nthe Iron Curtain, opened the exhibit\nat 11 A. BL, March 21.\nThe display of photographs, texts,\nmaps and charts is largely from Com-\nmunist sources, assembled by refu-\ngees from Albania, Bulgaria, Cxecho\n\u25a0lovakia, Estonia, Hungary, Latvia,\nLithuania, Poland and Rumania.\nWhile stating that some improve\nmeats have been made, Mitchell point\ned out that \u201ccoverage size of bene\nfits and duration still tall short of' the\nstandards the Administration has\nbeen recommending in recent years.\".\nshould like to take' this oppor\ntunity to express a concern which I '1,\nknow you share,\u201d he wrote, \u201cthat taw\ning this period of unemployment com\npwisation claims be processed with, ff IjIJi","height":"25596","width":"20144"}}
